	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Druids are a fun class because they can do so many different things.&nbsp;&nbsp;But as Iteck has pointed out, they don’t do them as well as other classes.  It’s a Jack-of-All-Trades and master of none type thing.  One of the things I like best about druids is their independence. As you gain levels you become very self-sufficient.  You can forage, or at least wood elves can, or summon your own food and water.  You can heal yourself.  You can speed up your movement and slow down or stop the movement of your enemies.  You can bind and gate yourself.  And by 19th level you can begin teleporting around Norrath.  When you reach 34th level you get an area effect spell that will allow you to quad kite, basically killing 4 monsters at the same time and gain experience fairly quickly.  And because of their mobility, druids are a good class for a trade skill character.  <br><br>In the end it just depends on how you like to play the game.  In a group, druids, like most casters, will find themselves standing up to cast and spell and sitting down to meditate their manna back.  If you want to do something more active, there are lots of classes that stand toe to toe with the monsters and beat them to death about the head and shoulders.  However, you give up most or all of your magic to gain this ability.  If you want to swing weapons and still have SOME druid spells, you might look into playing a ranger.  I play both, depending on how bloodthirsty I feel at the moment.  *grins*  <br><br>&nbsp;<br><b>Pait Spiritwalker</b><br>Vah Shir Shaman, 52nd Season<br><b>Namir Shadowstalker</b><br>Wood Elf Ranger, 51st Season<br><b>Calabar Silverthorn</b><br>Wood Elf Druid, 51st Season<br><br><b>Seventh Hammer</b> </td></tr>
